//-------------------------------------- variables in js 

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
  <h2>Variables Demo</h2>
  <script>
    var oldVar = "I am var";     // function scoped
    let newVar = "I am let";     // block scoped
    const fixedVar = "I cannot change"; // constant

    document.write(oldVar + "<br>");
    document.write(newVar + "<br>");
    document.write(fixedVar + "<br>");
  </script>
</body>
</html>


//----------------------------------data types 

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
  <h2>Data Types</h2>
  <script>
    let name = "Shahid";   // String
    let age = 25;          // Number
    let isStudent = true;  // Boolean
    let marks;             // Undefined
    let empty = null;      // Null

    document.write(typeof name + "<br>");
    document.write(typeof age + "<br>");
    document.write(typeof isStudent + "<br>");
    document.write(typeof marks + "<br>");
    document.write(typeof empty + "<br>");
  </script>
</body>
</html>
//----------------------DOM 

    üå≥ What is DOM in JavaScript?

DOM (Document Object Model) is a programming interface for HTML and XML documents.
It represents the page so that programs (like JavaScript) can manipulate the structure, style, and content dynamically.

üëâ In simple words: DOM is the tree structure representation of an HTML page.
Each tag in HTML becomes a node in the DOM tree (like <html>, <body>, <h1>, etc.).

üìå Why DOM is Important?

JavaScript can access and change HTML elements.

JavaScript can change CSS styles dynamically.

JavaScript can react to user events (click, input, hover, etc.).

DOM makes your page interactive.

üñºÔ∏è DOM Representation (Tree Example)

HTML:

<html>
  <body>
    <h1>Hello Students</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph</p>
  </body>
</html>


DOM Tree:

Document
 ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ html
      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ body
           ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ h1 ‚Üí "Hello Students"
           ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ p  ‚Üí "This is a paragraph"


